    "body": "nd do bolt on kits exist to conver to haudralic? Yes — bolt-on kits do exist for converting a Land Cruiser J40 to hydraulic power steering, but there’s an important catch: 👉 Almost none are truly 100% bolt-on. They are usually “conversion kits” that reduce fabrication, but most still require some welding or drilling. Example hydraulic conversion kits for the J40 Complete Saginaw power steering kit A typical example is a Saginaw conversion kit like the one from Cruiser Solutions. It normally includes: power steering gearbox steering shaft pump pump bracket mounting plate pitman arm drag link high and low pressure hoses pulley and belt system These kits run roughly $1,100–$1,600 depending on completeness. Installation reality Even with a kit: Typical work required: Weld steering box mounting plate to frame Drill or cut hole in front crossmember Modify steering column Install pump bracket and pulley The steering box mount must be welded because it carries very high steering forces, and installers recommend a certified welder. So the kits are “semi-bolt-on”, not truly plug-and-play. Types of kits you’ll see There are basically three J40 conversion styles. 1️⃣ Saginaw steering conversion Most common worldwide. Uses: GM steering box GM pump Pros: very strong easy parts availability Cons: most fabrication 2️⃣ Toyota mini-truck box conversion Uses steering box from: 1979–1985 Toyota pickup / Hilux Pros: more compact more “Toyota” Cons: still some welding 3️⃣ FJ60 steering box conversion Uses steering from the 60-series Land Cruiser. Pros: extremely robust good steering feel popular with big tyres Cons: slightly more complex install The closest thing to “bolt-on” There are kits that provide all mounting plates and shafts, so you just install the steering box and pump. But even those still require: welding one mount drilling a crossmember There’s no true IKEA-style bolt-on hydraulic kit because the original J40 chassis was never designed for power steering. The r