    "body": "Hamza Syed\n\n  • 1st\n\n--\n\n1w • Edited • \n\n\n\nI almost said no to speaking at NothingFest 2025.\n\nWhen Professor Rohma Khan Khan invited me, I was slightly apprehensive after seeing the list of past speakers in the information pack. They included former foreign ministers, senators, and well-known figures in the arts.\n\nNothingFest, a dynamic week-long exhibition hosted at Beaconhouse National University (BNU), Pakistan’s leading liberal arts university, by the Mariam Dawood School of Visual Arts & Design (SVAD) and the UNESCO Chair on Inclusion Through Art.\n\nProfessor Rohma insisted I had something worth sharing. I rejected the invitation immediately. She insisted again. I still declined, feeling like a complete imposter.\n\nAfter a few days reflecting on how important it is to step outside one’s comfort zone, I decided to speak.\n\nAt 18, an unintentional psilocybin experience, the active compound found in magic mushrooms, lifted me out of a decade-long clinical depression.\n\nA mushroom. A bloody mushroom.\n\nA fungus growing quietly in forests vanquished ten years of suicidal thoughts.\n\nUniversities such as John Hopkins University, Imperial College London and University of California, Berkeley now host the world’s most advanced research centres and laboratories leading serious work on psychedelics, exploring their potential in treating mental disorders and deepening our understanding of consciousness.\n\nThat moment became the inflection point that set the course for everything that followed.\n\nBut the rupture began earlier.\n\nAt eleven, at Dragon School Oxford, where my sense of self first fractured. What followed was the jagged experience of growing up bi-cultural in Modern Britain — learning to inhabit two worlds at once. Somewhere around that time I slipped into a long stretch of depression.\n\nSpeaking to art students, I used the history of Venice to illustrate the cyclical nature of existence, from individuals to nations and empires, and ultimately entire civilisations: rupture, decay, and reinvention.\n\nBuilding Legends Academy Pakistan now feels like participating consciously in that cycle of Pakistan’s development journey, if even in a small way.\n\nAbove all, I hope the students left with a sense of optimism for Pakistan, recognising the boundless opportunities here rather than contributing to the brain drain.\n\nAnd if I didn’t bore them… perhaps I’ll be invited back. \n\n(The talk has been recorded & happy to share the link — just DM me).",
